			<tr>
				<td colspan="2">
					
					


<font face="verdana" size="2"><p><b>Compatible races:</b></font><br>


<font face="verdana" size="1">
<a href='classes.asp?CID=24&mode=details&type=classes'>Dark Elf</a>, <a href='classes.asp?CID=26&mode=details&type=classes'>Erudite</a>, <a href='classes.asp?CID=27&mode=details&type=classes'>Gnome</a>, <a href='classes.asp?CID=30&mode=details&type=classes'>High Elf</a>, <a href='classes.asp?CID=31&mode=details&type=classes'>Human</a>
<font face="verdana" size="3"><p><b>Guide:</b></font><br><br>
<font face="verdana" size="2">
<p><font face="Verdana" size="2"><strong>What Race to choose</strong></font></p>

<p><font face="Verdana" size="2">I started out with an Erudite Wizard,  which gave me
the maximum amount of <a href="http://www.everlore.com/default.asp?mode=20&id=40">intelligence</a>
you can get.  The only thing I can say is that as you increase in level the most
important thing to a wizard is the amount of mana he or she has.  I definitely don't
think that Erudites are the best,  it is just what I chose.  All classes and
race combinations seem to be pretty well balanced.  So choose what you like.  </font></p>

<p><font face="Verdana" size="2"><strong>Starting out: Levels 1-3</strong></font></p>

<p><font face="Verdana" size="2">First thing is to memorize your spells.  You can
accomplish this by placing your scrolls in the spells slots on the spell screen.  For
a detailed explanation read the EverQuest Manual.  After that you want to practice at
the local wizards guild.  The guild locations vary so I wont go into that.  Than
spend one skill practice point in  <a
href="http://www.everlore.com/skills/default.asp?mode=5&id=568">Fishing</a> and <a
href="http://www.everlore.com/skills/default.asp?mode=5&id=588">Piercing</a> to give
them a jump start.  This is recommended but no completely necessary.  You can
gain skill without putting any practice points in them.  Key thing to remember is to
not use all of your practice points.  What you want to do is save them for later.
  More on that below.</font></p>

<p><font face="Verdana" size="2">After the guild you are ready to fight 1 level beasties.
  This is were the fun begins.  You can, if you wish practice your two spells <a
href="http://www.everlore.com/magic/Magic.asp?ID=87&mode=details&spname=Shock+of+Frost">shock
of frost</a> and <a
href="http://www.everlore.com/magic/Magic.asp?ID=72&mode=details&spname=Minor+Shielding">minor
shielding</a> before you start fighting, but this is not completely necessary.  What
I mean by practicing is,  target yourself by clicking on, or around your blue heath
meter on the top right of your play screen, and then cast <a
href="www.everlore.com/magic/Magic.asp?ID=87&mode=details&spname=Shock+of+Frost">shock
of frost</a>.  What this will accomplish is you will start to raise your <a
href="http://www.everlore.com/skills/default.asp?mode=5&id=566">Evocation</a> skill
without paying for it.  Same for <a
href="www.everlore.com/magic/Magic.asp?ID=72&mode=details&spname=Minor+Shielding">Minor
Shielding</a>. This way you save your practice points and you better prepare yourself for
the future first level combat.  I didn't do this because if you die you just get
placed right back in the newbie zone anyway,  and the skills <a
href="http://www.everlore.com/skills/default.asp?mode=5&id=566">Evocation</a> and <a
href="http://www.everlore.com/skills/default.asp?mode=5&id=537">Abjuration</a> raise
very quickly.  Ok, now head to the first zone outside your starting point and start
hacking those snakes or whatever out there.  Remember,  don't attack anything
that is not White to you.  What that means is, when you target a creature by clicking
on it and press the "C" key,  the message, in your message viewer displays
in white that this creatures is even to you in level.  Any creature that is yellow or
red is higher level than you and should be avoided, any creature blue or green is lower
level than you.  Blues and whites are what you want to focus on through to level 4.
  At this time don't worry about food and water,  because you get it back when
you die,  all you need to worry about is raising your skills and getting to level 4.</font></p>

<p><font face="Verdana" size="2"><strong>Ahh!!: Level 4-7</strong></font></p>

<p><font face="Verdana" size="2">Ok what spells can I get NOW!  Yes you get some, you
worthless wizard.  You get <a
href="http://www.everlore.com/magic/Magic.asp?ID=177&mode=details&spname=Shock+of+Fire">Shock
of Fire</a> and <a
href="http://www.everlore.com/magic/Magic.asp?ID=156&mode=details&spname=Root">Root</a>!
You want to by Root first and Shock of Fire Second.  You really want them both but if
I had to choose it would be root.  Now you want to practice this spell until you max.
  Once you max your skill go out and start to lump up beasties from afar.  Cast
root and then light them up, that's it!  Once they free themselves they will becoming
after you so be prepared with your <a
href="http://www.everlore.com/items/items.asp?mode=details&id=630&type=weapon">dagger</a>
or <a
href="http://www.everlore.com/items/items.asp?mode=details&id=626&type=weapon">staff</a>.
  By the way if you are lucky enough to have a staff at this point it is the
preferred weapon of a Wizard.</font></p>

<p><font face="Verdana" size="2">Also now is a good time to find a friend that is the same
level as you.  Fighter type classes, wizards, and magicians are good for a twosome.
  Fighters of course are a great way to raise levels because he will be keeping that
creature off of you.  Same goes for Magicians and there little pets.  I prefer
parting with other wizards though!</font></p>

<p><font face="Verdana" size="2"><em>Good things about partying with another Wizard</em>:
This is because when you are fighting a creature you need the creature to be away from
you.  You cast root then fire away,  the creature than gets released and is on
top of you.  Now your partner if he is a wizard can cast root on it.  Once
rooted for a second time you both can start blasting away.</font></p>

<p><font face="Verdana" size="2"><strong>Levels 8 - 11:</strong></font></p>

<p><font face="Verdana" size="2">Well I'm only level 10, so basically what I can tell you
is Buy Shock of Ice, its a must have!  This does about 36 hits of damage against most
creatures.  Also,  the root and shoot tactics still are your bread and butter if
you are soloing.  Most of the time you need another party member or you will be
dieing alot or fighting lots of low level creatures.</font></p>

<p><font face="Verdana" size="2"> </font></p>

<p><font face="Verdana" size="2"><strong>Misc.:</strong></font></p>

<p><font face="Verdana" size="2">I have played a monk a magician and now a wizard and I'm
still undecided on whether a Magician or a Wizard is the one for me.  For now I'm
sticking with a wizard.  Everyone's different so play what you like.  </font></p>

<p><font face="Verdana" size="2">Happy Hunting</font></p>

<p><font face="Verdana" size="2">Eldwin</font></p>

<p> </p>

<p> </p>

					
					</p></font>
				</td>
